Here are my notes from Mission, Vision, and Values: Vision : LCW envisions a world where… …all individuals are empowered to freely unlock their potential. …inclusion is embedded into all organizational strategies. …organizations inspire sustainable workplace inclusion and cultural competence globally. …all workplaces maintain and nurture a sustainable culture of inclusion. …cultural competence is embedded into how everyone treats each other. More: inclusion, aspirational, workplaces, inspiring organizations/workplaces/stakeholders. Less: words. Mission : LCW strives to make its clients’ mindsets and systems culturally competent, so they can meet their goals in ways that unlock everyone’s potential, talents, and contributions. Values: We talked about connecting with: Wowing the client, Advocating for people and groups who have less power in any given organization, fun, finding a way (ingenuity, resourcefulness). Cultural Detective African American (https://www.culturaldetective.com/what/series-content/66:africa-american.html) I have the honor to be a co-author and as we are coming into Kwanzaa and Black History month I encourage all to learn and grow while exploring and understanding the African American Culture. For now without googling , please think and answer TRUE or FALSE: - The name Kwanzaa comes from an African phrase “ matunda ya kwanza” meaning first fruits. - Kwanzaa is a West African tradition proudly celebrated in the USA. - Slaves in the deep south were allowed to celebrate Kwanzaa. - Kwanzaa starts December 26 every year. - Kwanzaa is not a religious tradition. - Kwanzaa follows 7 principles that build community. > - About 5% of the U.S population celebrate Kwanzaa HAPPY HOLIDAYS!

DID YOU KNOW? December has marked the end of the year and the coming of winter since the ancient Romans established their first calendar. As its etymology indicates, December is formed from the Latin root decem- which means “ten” … but December is our twelfth month, not sure why but the joke is that people are in holiday mode since end of October, so maybe our mind is stuck at 10th month??? 😊 The holiday season in the United States is generally considered to begin the day after Halloween and end after New Year's Day. There are many observances in the United States in December, including religious holidays, international days, and other holidays: - Christmas : A Christian holiday that celebrates the birth of Jesus Christ /December 25 2024 - Hanukkah : An eight-day Jewish holiday that celebrates the rededication of the Holy Temple Dec 25,2024 to Jan 02,2025 - Kwanzaa : A holiday that is commonly celebrated in the United States and around the world by many now Dec 26 2024-Jan 01,2025 - World AIDS Day : An international day to show support for people living with HIV, honor those who have died from AIDS-related illnesses, and fight against HIV - International Day for the Abolition of Slavery : An international day to raise awareness of modern slavery and the human rights violations it causes December 02,2024 - International Day of Persons with Disabilities : An international day to create accessible and inclusive societies for people with disabilities December 03.2024 - Feast of the Holy Family : A Catholic liturgical celebration that honors Jesus, his mother, and St. Joseph December 29,2024 - Watch Night : A Christian day for reflection, confession, prayer, and resolution for the year ahead but also Watch Night or “Freedom's Eve,” when African Americans watched and waited for the news of Freedom. An annual New Year's Eve tradition that includes the memory of slavery and freedom, reflections on faith, and celebration of community and strength. Dec 31, 2024 HAPPY HOLIDAYS!

DID YOU KNOW???? November is National Gratitude Month: It started in 2015, thanks to Stacey Grewal, an author and inspirational speaker who wanted a dedicated time to focus on gratitude, which led to the month-long celebration every November. This month encourages people to express thanks and appreciate the positives in their lives, fostering a culture of gratitude that can lead to a happier and more fulfilling life. Grewal’s initiative quickly gained traction, with communities and organizations adopting various ways to participate. Activities like gratitude journaling, thank-you notes, and public gratitude walls became popular methods to engage people in the spirit of thankfulness. These practices help individuals recognize and appreciate the good in their daily lives, promoting mental and emotional well-being. Over the years, National Gratitude Month has grown in popularity, incorporating new traditions and activities. Social media campaigns, workshops, and community events now play a significant role in spreading the message of gratitude. This month-long celebration continues to evolve, encouraging people to make gratitude a regular part of their lives, leading to stronger relationships and a more positive outlook. This month-long celebration also reminds us to acknowledge and appreciate the contributions of others. It can strengthen bonds within families, friendships, and communities. By making gratitude a daily habit, people can create a more empathetic and connected world, enhancing overall well-being for everyone involved.

November 11th was ARMISTICE for me and ALL of FRANCE was OFF, when many in the US worked and even some schools were open. Armistice Day (which coincides with Remembrance Day and Veterans Day, public holidays) is commemorated every year on 11 November to mark the Armistice of 11 November 1918 signed between the Allies of World War I and the German Empire at Compiègne, France, for the cessation of hostilities on the Western Front of World War I, which took effect at eleven o'clock in the morning, the "eleventh hour of the eleventh day of the eleventh month" of 1918. I had a great weekend full of hugs and great conversations locally and globally. As have family in Europe who have served in several wars including WWI, connecting with family made me realize what the word FIGHT & FREEDOM really mean BUT also as we spoke about the US elections’ results, the conversation came to express that CESSATION OF HOSTILITIES is something the USA could embrace for the good of ALL AMERICANS, so we could really call ourselves UNITED STATES OF AMERICA . Once again, understanding culture through global traditions, holidays etc. gives us a well needed boost of cultural competence.

How do we narrate historical events? And from whose perspective? One of the core missions of intercultural education is to increase the awareness about “Colonial” perspective and words we often use without even awareness. Narratives have shaped our understanding of history and too often, we use terms without realizing their impact, perpetuating a Eurocentric view. Taking in consideration diverse cultural perspectives and showing respect for cultural differences mean also starting a process of decolonization of our mindset of our use of language. For many, this date does not symbolize a discovery but rather the beginning of a painful history of colonization, exploitation, and cultural loss. In Argentina, October 12th is celebrated as Día del Respeto a la Diversidad Cultural (Day of Respect for Cultural Diversity), rather than focusing on the “discovery” narrative. It’s a day to honour cultural differences and promote reflection on our shared histories. Some regions informally call it Día de la Amistad. Happy Lantern Festival - the last day of Chinese New Year/Spring Festival! This festival It celebrates family reunions, socializing and freedom, while also featuring ancient spiritual traditions. On the 15th day of the new year - the Lantern Festival - everyone takes to the streets to celebrate and light lanterns. Some regard the festival as the “true” Chinese Valentine’s Day, rather than the more traditional day of Qixi. Despite its importance, the Lantern Festival isn’t a national holiday, so there are no days off for celebrations. #China #YearoftheTiger

I just finished this book and wanted to recommend for anyone interested. For me it was an opportunity to continue to deepen my understanding of LGBTQ+ communities, especially those making the decision to live in seemingly hostile areas of the country outside of big, liberal bastions along the coast. I got that understanding and more. The author, Samantha Allen, also courageously weaves throughout the book her own story of being transgender in red state America. I didn't expect that, for some reason. It was revelatory. I could not recommend it enough. https://www.them.us/story/summer-book-club-real-queer-america-interview (https://www.them.us/story/summer-book-club-real-queer-america-interview)
